Question 1

Given the relationship between x1, x2, and y, I would tune my kNN, LDA, and Decision tree algorithms differently. Graphing the given variables, x1^2 + x2^2 = ___ produces a circle. Points that are within a circle with radius 5 produce y=0. while points outside of that circle produce y=1.

kNN: kNN, or k-Nearest Neighbour Classification works by classifying a data point based on its “nearest neighbor”, which is usually measured using points by Euclidean distance. kNN would classify new points as y=1 or y=0 by checking what its nearest neighbors are classified as. If most of the nearby points are inside the circle with radius 5, the new point would be classified as y=0, and y=1 if nearby points are outside the circle. Euclidean distance would work well in this case, since the “boundary” is circular. Regarding tuning, I would choose a low k value, like k=1, k=3 or k=5; this would cause the model to be more sensitive, and rely on the closest one, three, or five neighbors. I think this would work well for general predictions, but the kNN might fail when classifying points that are on/near the border of the circle, as that might lead to inaccurate classifications if the nearest points are on the other side of the border. Additionally, since kNN works by taking the majority, I would choose an odd number for a k-value. Overall, I think kNN would perform well with this relationship, as it doesn’t make any assumptions about the data and relies on Euclidean distance to make predictions.

LDA: LDA, or linear discriminant analysis works by finding a linear combination of the input variables to separate the two outcomes (y=1 or y=2). Since the boundary in this question is non-linear(circular), I’m not sure that any tuning would help, as LDA would not recognize the circular boundary.

Decision Tree: A decision tree breaks down a data set into smaller subsets based on variable conditions. To tune the tree so that it would recognize the circular boundary, I would control the tree’s depth using maxdepth and set a higher depth. This would allows the tree to create more splits, helping it approximate the circular boundary. I would also fiddle with complexity parameter (cp), I think I would set it lower cp to increase splits, to approximate the circular boundary.

Question 2

The scenario would be absolutely terrible if the model was just guessing randomly, and unable to distinguish between Class A and Class B beyond random chance, and just predicts with 50% accuracy by guessing randomly (like flipping a coin). This would be terrible because a model that just predicts Class A would already achieve 95% percent accuracy, so it would be even worse than that. One example could be detecting a type of cancer in patients, where class A (95%) indicated no cancer/healthy, while class B (5%) indicated cancer/unhealthy. In this terrible case, it would predict that for every healthy person, there’s a 50% chance the model says they have cancer, and for every person with cancer, there’s a 50% chance the model says they’re not healthy. The model would basically do nothing.

The scenario would be very mediocre if it achieved 50% accuracy by assigning observations in Class A to Class B (and from class B to class A. This is better than absolutely terrible (which is just guessing randomly), but it would still misclassify a lot, but at least it is not doing it randomly. Going back to the cancer example, in this mediocre case, it would correctly assign some patients with cancer, but it would also incorrectly classify some patients who don’t have cancer with cancer (thats ok, but not great). However, it would correctly classify patients who don’t have cancer, and would incorrectly classify patients who have cancer with not having cancer (this is really bad). Overall, it would not be great, but still better than randomly choosing.

The model would be quite impressive if the model successfully predicted all 5% in class B, classified 45% of class A correctly, and then incorrectly classified the rest of class A as class B. In the cancer example, this would be if it correctly classified all 5% of patients who have cancer with cancer, and then correctly classified 45% percent of healthy patients as healthy. The shortfall is that it would incorrectly classify 50% of healthy people with having cancer, but this is less important because all patients with cancer will end up being treated. The patients who had false positives could get second opinions.

Normalizing Data for kNN and training

stroke_scaled <- stroke_cleaned |>
  na.omit() |>
  mutate(scaled_heart =
           (heart_disease - min(heart_disease))/(max(heart_disease) - min(heart_disease))) |>
  mutate(scaled_age =
           (age - min(age, na.rm=TRUE))/(max(age, na.rm=TRUE)-min(age, na.rm=TRUE))) |>
  mutate(scaled_glucose =
           (avg_glucose_level- min(avg_glucose_level, na.rm=TRUE))/(max(avg_glucose_level, na.rm=TRUE)- min(avg_glucose_level, na.rm=TRUE)))

stroke_thing <- expand_grid(scaled_heart = seq(from = 0, to = 1, by = .05),
                                  scaled_age = seq(from = 0, to = 1, by = .05),
                                  scaled_glucose = seq(from = 0, to = 1, by = .05))

Question 4

It makes sense that the cost of a false positive would be C, while the cost of a false positive would be ten times higher at 10 C. This means that missing a stroke case is ten times more costly than incorrectly predicting one —similar to question 2. I would tune the models to be more sensitive and predict strokes more often, because even if there were false positives, that would be better than false negatives. In kNN, I would choose a lower K value, because it would be more influenced by nearby points, and since there is a low percentage of positives overall, negatives might affect it less. To make LDA more sensitive, I would change the prior values, to something like c(0.6, 0.4). Setting higher prior probability for the stroke class can help LDA focus more on detecting strokes, which might increase sensitivity. For the tree, I would choose a lower cp, so that the tree can grow larger, there also some other variables like maxdepth that I could change to make it more sensitive. I think LDA or decision tree would be the best model to predict a stroke with these new “costs”, as just changing the k value for kNN might not do much.

Here is a new lda with changed priors. It actually does pretty well with predicting strokes, but gives more false positives.
